someone is using the wrong word?  Proposed generally means "not built yet". 
 If the airport and/or hangar doesn't exist yet, then it can't house the 
plane, no two ways around that.
About the other pilot that heard a static-filled transmission whom he 
believed was the copilot... Did he know this gentleman personally, to be 
able to recognize the voice without identification and amidst all the 
static?  And why was the copilot mumbling...because if I were having an 
emergency, I sure as heck wouldn't be mumbling, I'd be making my voice 
HEARD.  But more importantly, how was the other pilot to know that the 
transmission came from this flight?

See these are the dangers of speculation.  Wild imagination coupled with 
abandonment of logic can produce an unlimited number of possibilities.

So my question to you is this:  What parts of this story are credible?  The 
cell phones ringing still after all this time?  Has anybody provided any 
public phone listings with phone numbers of any of the actual passengers? 
 I don't believe this is credible, so not likely a 'fact' to be considered.
The other pilot with a static-filled transmission hearing mumbling (which 
by definition is unintelligible) but still could identify the other plane's 
copilot?  Not credible to me either...scratch that one off the 'fact' list 
too.
Proposed airports?  IF we consider this possibility then let's only 
consider airports that actually have been built...but since there is no 
empirical evidence that the plane even ventured close, then we'll put the 
proposed airports, and even the country, on the back burner for now.

up.﻿
